results.notes:
Two mature fruiting bodies on a heavily myceliated/decorticated section of an Acer macrophyllum stump.

Cap: convex, whitish(lower specimen stained heavily pink from spore drop of upper fruiting
body). Center of cap slightly granulose/scaly.

Gills: stained heavily pinkish brown from spore drop. Lots of alternating short gills.
Gills free from stem apex.

Stem: white, WITHOUT blackish streaking, stained pinkish from deposited spores. Slightly swollen at base.

Odor: slightly radish like.

Taste: mild.

Harvested a single specimen for further study/microscopy.

MICROSCOPY:
Mounted gill tissue in KOH. Shots of my work included in observation.
Cheilocystidia: very few. Only 2 on entire gill analyzed.
Intermediate cystidia: without projections.

Spore printed a portion of cap directly on a second glass slide for spore deposit and additional microscopy.

Spore Print: Pink.
Mounted in KOH:
Spores: ellipsoid, smooth with a single droplet(guttule) inside most all spores analyzed.
See also images of work included here.
Spores are noticeably smaller than P. cervinus group.
Dehydrated specimen thoroughly and bagged for herbarium collection/genetic record.

results.notes:
Three mature fruiting bodies on a fallen Western Hemlock. Monitored this collection from earlier this summer to today.
Cap: completely coated in thick layer of deposited spores(electrostatically dispersed and collecting back in repeated circular motion onto caps). Caps completely laccate, deep maroon beneath spore coating(see images included).
Stem: thick, lateral, dark maroon, laccate(see images included after harvest).
Pore surface: white, staining brown where handled/scraped. Pores are large 2-3 per mm.
Harvested two specimens for later medicinal use in tea/tincture. Sliced vertically with serrated bread knife and dehydrated thoroughly.
Scraped off large sections of thick spore deposit from cap edge and mounted in KOH on slides(included images of process).
Spore print: dark cinnamon brown.
Microscopy:
Collected spores mounted in KOH and analyzed with my Celestron digital scope(images shot with my cell phone stabilized at the view screen).
Spores: very large, thick walled with geoduck like appendage at one end(see multiple photos included of work performed).
Bagged a single slice from each specimen(two total in voucher bag for this collection for genetic record).

A potent Psilocybe Cubensis strain derived from a cross between Melmac Penis Envy and APE (Albino Penis Envy). This unique lineage results in a highly potent strain that delivers deep experiences for novices and experienced users alike.

Makilla Gorilla mushrooms boast large, fist-sized dried fruits, pale colourless stems, and light golden brown caps. The thick, circular caps and heavy blue bruising on the stems signal their high psilocybin content. For those new to psilocybin, Makilla Gorilla offers a powerful introduction to its transformative effects. Users report a captivating sensory experience. The strain is known for generating vivid, open-eye visuals, immersing trippers in a world of vibrant colours and intricate geometric patterns, reminiscent of a kaleidoscope.

In addition to the striking visuals, a mild dose of Makilla Gorilla can also impart a profound sense of relaxation through a body high that is both enjoyable and manageable. This harmonious blend of sensory enhancement and physical tranquility makes for a uniquely engaging psilocybin experience.
